  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cyclical Issuance:</strong> Credit ratings revenue is tied to corporate debt issuance. If interest rates rise rapidly and debt markets freeze, revenue will drop.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Pressure:</strong> As an oligopoly, rating agencies face constant scrutiny. New regulations could increase compliance costs.</li>
    <li><strong>M&A Integration:</strong> Acquisitions (like IHS Markit) bring integration risks and potential goodwill impairments if synergies are not fully realized.</li>
    <li><strong>Discount Rate Sensitivity:</strong> Because cash flows are weighted towards the terminal value, slight changes in the required rate of return drastically alter the valuation.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying, which varies wildly with sentiment. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about cash generation and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why an {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents the required return. The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. Adding a market risk premium for a stable business like S&P Global leads us to 9% — a fair hurdle rate for this high-quality compounder.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

